# AIDE-Lite Deploy Workflow

After EVERY code change (no matter how small), you MUST follow this exact sequence before considering the task complete:

## Step 1 — Close Studio Pro

```powershell
$sp = Get-Process -Name "studiopro" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if ($sp) {
    $sp | Stop-Process -Force
    Start-Sleep -Seconds 3
}
```

Wait until the process is fully gone before proceeding.

## Step 2 — Build

```powershell
dotnet build src\AideLite.csproj -c Release
```

If the build fails, fix the errors and rebuild. Do NOT proceed to copy on a failed build.

## Step 3 — Copy to Studio Pro Extensions

```powershell
$dest = "C:\Users\tomekgolembiewski\AppData\Local\Programs\Mendix\10.24.13.86719\modeler\Extensions\AideLite"
if (Test-Path $dest) { Remove-Item $dest -Recurse -Force }
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path $dest -Force | Out-Null
Copy-Item -Path "src\bin\Release\net8.0-windows\*" -Destination $dest -Recurse -Force
```

## Step 4 — Launch Studio Pro with project

```powershell
Start-Process "C:\Users\tomekgolembiewski\AppData\Local\Programs\Mendix\10.24.13.86719\modeler\studiopro.exe" -ArgumentList "`"C:\MendixProjects\LEA-development-current\Zeiterfassung 2024.mpr`""
```

This opens Studio Pro directly into the project without the startup dialog.

## Important Notes

- All shell commands require `required_permissions: ["all"]` to access paths outside the workspace.
- NEVER skip this workflow. The user expects the extension to be deployed and Studio Pro running after every change.
- If Studio Pro is not running in Step 1, skip straight to Step 2.
- Always verify the build succeeded (exit code 0) before copying.
- The `.mpr` project path above is per-project. If the user switches to a different Mendix project, ask them for the new `.mpr` path and update Step 4 accordingly.
